Article content extracted:
Kennedy Wafula Waliaula, better known by his pen name Ken Walibora ( 6 January 1965 – 10 April 2020 ) was a Kenyan writer, journalist, and scholar. He is a known figure in Kenyan Swahili literature, having authored Swahili books, which is Kenya's national language. His books Siku Njema and Kidagaa Kimemwozea were used as a national setbook for Kiswahili literature in Kenyan secondary schools.
Ken Walibora was born in Baraki, Bungoma District (present-day Bungoma County) of the Western Province in 1965 and grew up in Cherangany and Kitale. He later changed his name to Walibora, with the suffix 'bora' meaning 'better/best' in Swahili. His mother's name was Ruth Makali.
Walibora attended St. Joseph's Primary School in western Kenya for his primary education. He then pursued his high school education at Teremi school and Suremi Secondary School and at Ole Kajiado High School.
He did his bachelor's degree at the University of Nairobi and graduated with a firstclass honors degree in Literature and Swahili studies. He proceeded to do his masters at Ohio University.
He was a writer and author of books in Swahili and wrote novels, poetry, short stories and essays... He on more than one occasions called out the government on the fact that the use Swahili, which is the national language, was being restricted in learning institutions...
He made contributions to book chapters and articles to academic journals...
He served as lecturer at Wisconsin Madison University and Riara University. He also worked as a Swahili news anchor and editor at KBC and Nation Media Group as a probation officer.
On 10 April 2020, Walibora was struck by a speeding minibus while crossing Landhies Road... At KNH, Walibora remained in the emergency unit for approximately 14 to 18 hours without receiving full treatment... before succumbing to his injuries.
Police launched an investigation into his death... The government pathologist Johansen Oduor after an autopsy, revealed he had a deep cut on the space between his thumb and the index finger, consistent with self defence. Police also discovered that Walibora had been having disputes with his publisher... The case was treated as a homicide and is still unresolved.
He was buried at his rural home in Makutano, Cherangany constituency...

