Evidence in page: 
Alexander "Skunder" Boghossian (Amharic: ኣሌክሳንደር እስንድር ቦጎሲያን; Armenian: Ալեքսանդր "Սկունդեր" Բողոսյան; July 22, 1937 – May 4, 2003) was an Ethiopian painter and professor active in the United States. Boghossian was one of the first, and by far the most acclaimed, contemporary Black artists from the African continent to gain international attention.

Alexander Boghossian ... was born on July 22, 1937 in Addis Ababa, Italian East Africa... He attended a traditional kindergarten where he was taught the Ge'ez script. In primary and secondary school, he was taught by both Ethiopian and foreign tutors and became fluent in Amharic, Armenian, English, and French. He studied art informally at the Teferi Mekonnen School... The following year Boghossian settled in London and studied at Saint Martin's School of Art, Central School of Art and Design, and Slade School of Fine Art under an Imperial scholarship. In 1957, Boghossian relocated to Paris and studied at the Académie de la Grande Chaumière and later at the Ecole Nationale Supérieure des Beaux Arts.

In 1966 he returned home, teaching at Addis Ababa's School of Fine Arts until 1969. In 1970 he emigrated to the United States, first to Atlanta, where he became acquainted with the Black Arts Movement and taught at Atlanta's Center for Black Art, then he moved to Washington, D.C., where he taught at Howard University from 1972 until 2001.

Boghossian was the first contemporary African artist to have his work purchased by the Musee d’Art Moderne in Paris in 1963. In 1965, the Museum of Modern Art in New York acquired his painting Juju's Wedding (1964).

On May 4, 2003 Boghossian died at Howard University Hospital in Washington, DC., aged 65.

Summary: 
Skunder Boghossian (1937–2003) was a highly acclaimed Ethiopian painter and professor who achieved international recognition as a contemporary Black artist. Born in Addis Ababa, he pursued art studies in London and Paris. His teaching career spanned from the School of Fine Arts in Addis Ababa to Howard University in Washington, D.C., where he taught from 1972 to 2001. He holds the distinction of being the first contemporary African artist to have artworks purchased by the Musée d'Art Moderne in Paris and the Museum of Modern Art in New York. This comprehensive overview of his life, education, and career milestones should provide the necessary context to determine if he matches your search.
