Evidence in page: 
Abstract During the conventional machining of Ti-6Al-4V alloy, large amounts of lubricants are required as cooling agents or cutting fluids to mitigate heating and tool wear. However, cutting fluids adversely impacts the operator's safety and environment. Dry machining was endorsed as an ideal sustainable alternative, but due to exceedingly high cutting temperatures, which rapidly reduce ... Dry machining with the help of coated tools is a sustainable alternative to eliminate the cutting fluids. The present work investigates the influence of AlCrN and TiAlN coating during the end milling of high-performance Ti-6Al-4 V super alloy. ... Minimum Quantity Lubrication nanofluid (MQL-nanofluid) is a viable sustainable alternative to conventional flood cooling and provides very good cooling and lubrication in the machining of difficult to cut materials such as titanium and Inconel. ... The current study investigates the effect of six different strategies on the flank tool wear, surface roughness and energy consumption during turning of titanium Ti-6Al-4V using uncoated carbide tool at certain speed and feed. The use of rapeseed vegetable oil in MQL and MQCL configuration turns out to be an overall sustainable alternative.

Summary: 
The search results successfully identify multiple academic resources and thesis-relevant studies addressing sustainable alternatives to conventional coolants for machining the Ti-6Al-4V alloy. The highlighted alternatives include dry machining (facilitated by 3D resonant techniques or advanced AlCrN and TiAlN coated tools), Minimum Quantity Lubrication (MQL) utilizing nanofluids, and MQL/MQCL configurations using rapeseed vegetable oil. This information directly contributes to the user's goal by offering concrete, scientifically-backed sustainable cooling strategies and links to the corresponding academic literature.
